# Error & Async UI States

## Three states required

Every user-facing async view must handle:

1. **Loading** — skeleton or spinner; avoid layout shift
2. **Error** — message + retry action; log details in dev only
3. **Empty** — explain why no data; suggest next action

## API errors

- `packages/api` throws `ApiError` with `status` and optional `code`
- Apps catch in hooks or page-level handlers; never swallow silently

```tsx
try {
  await getApi().auth.login(credentials);
} catch (e) {
  if (e instanceof ApiError && e.status === 401) {
    setError("Invalid credentials");
  } else {
    setError("Something went wrong. Please try again.");
  }
}
```

## Reusable wrapper pattern

```tsx
type AsyncContentProps<T> = {
  isLoading: boolean;
  error: Error | null;
  isEmpty: boolean;
  children: (data: T) => React.ReactNode;
  data: T | undefined;
};

// Render: loading → error → empty → children(data)
```

Place shared `AsyncContent` in `apps/*/src/components/` (per-app) until a third reuse justifies `packages/ui`.

## Don'ts

- Don't fetch in render body — use `useEffect`, event handlers, or data hooks
- Don't show raw `error.message` from API to end users
- Don't leave buttons enabled during in-flight requests
